replies.bodyText:
ObjectNode is used for both internal cosmos types, and also for user apis.
as cosmos is a schema less database, we also would like to provide a schema less type, for that reason we also support ObjectNode in the public surface area. The other reason for supporting ObjectNode in the public surface area is perf as deserialization to ObjectNode doesn't require reflection whereas for deserializing to user provivded Pojo, jackson will use reflection which is slow.
As an example all of the following public API invocation currently work:
UserPojo userPojo = cosmosContainer.readItem(id, pk, UserPojo.class).block().getItem();
ObjectNode objectNode = cosmosContainer.readIteam(id, pk, ObjectNode.class).blcok.getItem();

btw, at least for jackson, ObjectMapper is capable of handling ObjectNode under the same API:
 static class UserPojo {
        @JsonProperty
        String id;

        @JsonProperty
        String pk;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {

        UserPojo userPojo = new UserPojo();
        userPojo.id = "myId";
        userPojo.pk = "mypk";

        ObjectMapper objectMapper = new ObjectMapper();
        byte[] bytes = objectMapper.writeValueAsBytes(userPojo);

        ObjectNode deserializedObjectNode = objectMapper.readValue(bytes, ObjectNode.class);
        UserPojo deserializedPojo = objectMapper.readValue(bytes, UserPojo.class);

        assert (deserializedObjectNode.get("id").asText().equals(deserializedPojo.id));

    }

